Interestingly, the author goes on to recommend<p><pre><code>  if(rc < 0) goto fail;
</code></pre>
as a countermeasure for that breed of bug.

Only if they&#x27;re not on the same line though. When you have<p><pre><code>    // ...
    if (rc < 0)
      return rc;
    // ...
</code></pre>
It&#x27;s easy to confuse the indentation for a block and end up with something like the apple bug.<p>But when you don&#x27;t break the line there&#x27;s no confusion:<p><pre><code>    // ...
    if (rc < 0) return c;
    // ...</code></pre>

Lines like that cause conditions to be missed (e.g. Apple&#x27;s goto fail bug)<p><pre><code>    if (rc < 0)
    {
      return rc;
    }
</code></pre>
always IMO.
